; the building of a low-rise, mixed-income "urban village" on the same site; and the conversion of one of the original buildings into a democratically governed, not-for-profit housing cooperative.The author argues that each of these projects involves imagining the physical, socioeconomic, and rhetorical community of the contemporary city in dramatically different ways. Considered together, the projects provide evidence that places still matter in human flourishing, but show that the places of our contemporary landscape are unequal in resources and opportunities, and that our public philosophies support this inequality. Fleming reminds us, however, that these arrangements are plastic and can be redesigned to reflect a more equitable sharing of public problems and resources.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunity development, UrbanzIllinoiszChicago. 0aInner citieszIllinoiszChicago. 0aUrban renewalzIllinoiszChicago. 4aAmerican Studies : American Studies. 4aCommunication : Communication. 4aLanguage Arts : Composition and Rhetoric Studies. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Philosophy. 4aSociology : Urban Studies. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Rhetoric.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978079147731140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791477311423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791477311/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles